The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, April 24, 2004 				 Billionaire Bhartis net soars
 OUR CORRESPONDENT				 	 Mittal in Delhi on Friday. (PTI)																								New Delhi, April 23: Bharti Tele-Ventures emerged as the fourth billion-dollar company in the last 10 days, after Infosys, Wipro and Ranbaxy. 																								The company has reported a net profit of Rs 619 crore in 2003-04 against a loss of Rs 134 crore in 2002-03. The company also posted a 64 per cent jump in revenue at Rs 5,002 crore for the year ended March 31, 2004 compared with Rs 3,050 crore in 2002-03.																								The telecom firms share closed at Rs 177.10 on the Bombay Stock Exchange today, an increase of Rs 9.20 over Thursdays close. Bharti, 28 per cent owned by Singapore Telecommunications, reported a consolidated net profit of Rs 304 crore for its fourth quarter compared with Rs 69.98 crore in the corresponding period last year and Rs 161 crore in the third quarter. In the fourth quarter, the company generated revenues of Rs 1,553 crore and EBIDTA of Rs 533 crore, registering a year-on-year growth of 54 per cent and 105 per cent and a sequential growth of 22 per cent and 13 per cent, respectively.																								Officials said its cash profit for 2003-04 grew by 190 per cent at Rs 1,430 crore against Rs 493 crore in 2002-03. EBIDTA has more than doubled from Rs 759 crore in 2002-03 to Rs 1,671 crore.																								The company said it was in a position to go in for an American depository receipts issue and was awaiting clearance from the government. Company executives also said once government policy issues like a hike in the foreign direct investment are cleared, Bharti would be able to finalise its ADR plans.																								Chairman and group MD Sunil Mittal said, This has been the most challenging year of my life. ... Focused strategy, improved execution, partnership with global leaders ... have now given us size and scale.																								We are a young company. Bharti represents the new generation telecom operators. Our focus would be to have a 21-25 per cent market share of the 100 million subscribers that has been projected by Trai, he said.
